<dl id="n53050g"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n53" href="#n53050g">N53 (VI.B.46)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n53all.htm#n53050g"> 50(g)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> <span class="strike"><span class="striketext">il vient</span></span> he is coming to come <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n53050g"><li>FW 598.10 </li><li><a href="../../flex/ta/lexta.htm#n53050g">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/ta/l39ta.htm#n53050g">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n53050g">MS BL 47488-49v</ms> </li><li>JJA 63:050 <a name="tad3" href="../../FF/fdra/tda.htm#tad3">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/ta/tad3.htm#n53050g">Draft: IV&sect;1.3</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[It is nice to see how in French the utmost proximity in time is conveyed by means of <i>spatial</i> expressions: <mark><i>Il vient d&apos;arriver</i></mark> and <i>Il va partir</i>. Both expressions are in fact pleonasms. &lsquo;He comes, he comes,&rsquo; i.e. He just came in; &lsquo;He goes, he goes&rsquo;, i.e. He just went out.]</font> <small> Fritz Mauthner, <a name="FMBK1" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#FMBK1"><cite title="source">Beitr&auml;ge zu einer Kritik der Sprache.</cite></a> 3 vols (1901-2) III 120</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
